 web of relations into an area of incomprehensible abstraction. And while the economization of life has come under widespread critique, inquiry into the political potential of representational praxis is more crucial than ever. This volume explores ethical, aesthetic and ideological dimensions of economic representation, redressing essential questions: What are the roles of mass and new media? How do the arts contribute to critical discourse on the global techno-economic complex? Collectively, the contributions bring theoretical debate and artistic intervention into a rich exchange that includes but also exceeds the conventions of academic scholarship.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 30. Aug 2021) 0aArt and society. 0aEconomicsxSociological aspects. 0aFinancexSocial aspects. 0aMass media and culture. 0aMass mediaxPhilosophy. 0aMoney. 4aCultural History. 4aCultural Studies. 4aCulture. 4aFinance. 4aMass Media. 4aMedia Aesthetics. 4aMedia Art. 4aMedia Representation. 4aMedia. 4aNew Media. 4aTechno-Economy. 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / Popular Culture.2bisacsh  aCultural History.  aCultural Studies.  aCulture.  aFinance.  aMass Media.  aMedia Aesthetics.  aMedia Art.  aMedia Representation.  aMedia.  aNew Media.  aTechno-Economy.1 aBorn, Marius, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aCuonz, Daniel, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aCuonz, Daniel, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aHaiven, Max, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aIndaco, Agustín, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aLangenohl, Andreas, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aLoren, Scott, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relator